  "prompt": "How do you determine the Lewis structure of SO2?",
  "response": "Determining the Lewis structure of sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082) involves several steps. Here's a step-by-step guide:\n\n1. **Count the valence electrons**: Sulfur (S) is in group 16 of the periodic table and has 6 valence electrons. Oxygen (O), also in group 16, has 6 valence electrons. Since there are two oxygen atoms, you multiply this by 2. Therefore, there are a total of \\( 6 (S) + 6 \\times 2 (O) = 18 \\) valence electrons.\n\n2. **Determine the central atom**: Sulfur is less electronegative than oxygen, so sulfur will be the central atom.\n\n3. **Create a skeleton structure**: Connect the sulfur atom with the two oxygen atoms using single bonds:\n   ```\n     O - S - O\n   ```\n\n4. **Distribute the remaining valence electrons**: After creating the skeleton structure, you have used 2 bonds (each bond counts as 2 electrons), so 2 \\(\\times\\) 2 = 4 electrons. Therefore, you have \\( 18 - 4 = 14 \\) electrons remaining. Distribute these 14 electrons to complete the octet for each oxygen atom and the sulfur atom.\n\n5. **Complete octets for oxygen atoms**: Each oxygen atom needs 8 electrons in total (including the bonding electrons). Each oxygen is bonded to sulfur with a single bond (2 electrons), so each needs 6 more electrons. Distribute 6 electrons around each oxygen:\n   ```\n     ..\n     O - S - O\n     ..\n   ```\n\n6. **Place remaining electrons on sulfur**: Now, sulfur has two electrons from each oxygen bond, so it currently has 4 electrons. It needs 8 electrons to complete its octet. Place the remaining 4 electrons around the sulfur atom:\n   ```\n     ...\n     O - S - O\n     ..\n   ```\n\n7. **Check for formal charges and octet rule**: At this point, you should check the formal charges on each atom. The formal charge can be calculated as:\n   \\[ \\text{Formal Charge} = \\text{Valence Electrons} - (\\text{Nonbonding Electrons} + \\text{Bonding Electrons}/2) \\]\n   For sulfur with this structure:\n   - Valence electrons = 6\n   - Non-bonding = 4\n   - Bonding pairs = 4/2 = 2 (1 from each bond with oxygen)\n\n   Formal Charge = 6 - (4 + 2) = 0\n\n   For each oxygen:\n   - Valence electrons = 6\n   - Non-bonding electrons = 6\n   - Bonding pairs with sulfur = 2/2 = 1\n\n   Formal Charge = 6 - (6 + 1) = -1\n\n   To reduce formal charges as perfectly as the real structure of this molecule, apply resonance structures (this is advanced level concept where bond shifts). \n\n8. **Establish resonance structure**: S and O double bond idea prevents unequal charges sometimes formalized for better symmetry in molecules:\n\n   The actual Lewis structure of SO\u2082 is more accurately represented as a resonance hybrid of two structures:\n\n   \\[\n     ..         ..\n    O = S - O   O - S = O\n    ..         ..\n   ```\n\n   This indicates delocalization of electrons.\n\nBy following these steps, you arrive at the Lewis structure for \\( SO_2 \\) that reflects its stability through resonance.",
